RouterFromDubiousLocationThatMacShouldntHaveBeenAt<br />
Starbucks Cupertino<br />
Ancient_Router_from_2007</code></p><p>The long command comes from <a href=\"https://coderwall.com/p/ghl-cg?i=10&#038;p=1&#038;q=sort%3Acreated_at+desc&#038;t%5B%5D=macos&#038;t%5B%5D=brew&#038;t%5B%5D=homebrew&#038;t%5B%5D=os+x&#038;t%5B%5D=mac\" target=\"_blank\">CoderWall</a> and though it may look strange, it&#8217;s required to get clean output. Entering the string without grep and sed will provide you with far more information than you are looking for in this case, as it it dumps out everything pertaining to past wi-fi connections that have become part of the &#8220;RememberedNetworks&#8221; list.</p></div><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=Qw3sIvnpCfg:ZwhzStJzx0o:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=Qw3sIvnpCfg:ZwhzStJzx0o:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?i=Qw3sIvnpCfg:ZwhzStJzx0o:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=Qw3sIvnpCfg:ZwhzStJzx0o:D7DqB2pKExk\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?i=Qw3sIvnpCfg:ZwhzStJzx0o:D7DqB2pKExk\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=Qw3sIvnpCfg:ZwhzStJzx0o:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=Qw3sIvnpCfg:ZwhzStJzx0o:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/osxdaily/~4/Qw3sIvnpCfg\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>") (wfw:commentRss nil "http://osxdaily.com/2012/12/21/list-wi-fi-networks-mac-has-connected-to-before/feed/") (slash:comments nil "0") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://osxdaily.com/2012/12/21/list-wi-fi-networks-mac-has-connected-to-before/"))) ("Quickly Locate iPhone Ringtones & Text Tones Stored Locally" "<div class=\"KonaBody\"><p><img src=\"http://cdn.osxdaily.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/iphone-ringtone-folder.jpg\" alt=\"iPhone ringtone folder\" title=\"iphone-ringtone-folder\" width=\"620\" height=\"246\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-35051\" /></p><p>iPhone ringtones and text tones – both of which are .m4r files – are stored in the same location in the file system, whether they were <a href=\"http://osxdaily.com/2010/09/04/make-free-iphone-ringtones-in-itunes-10/\">made with iTunes</a>, bought from the iTunes Store, <a href=\"http://osxdaily.com/2012/08/18/convert-any-audio-or-video-to-iphone-ringtone-easily/\">converted from another format</a> with QuickTime, or whether you downloaded them from elsewhere.</p><p>The ringtone storage folder in OS X is:</p><p><code>~/Music/iTunes/iTunes Media/Tones/</code></p><p>In Windows, they will be stored in the  \\My Music\\iTunes Media\\Tones\\, though the precise location will vary slightly depending on which version of Windows you’re using.</p><p>There are two ways to quickly get there on the Mac (the iTunes method works in Windows as well, however):</p><ul><li><strong>Finder:</strong> the <a href=\"http://osxdaily.com/2011/08/31/go-to-folder-useful-mac-os-x-keyboard-shortcut/\">infinitely useful Go To Folder</a> function works by hitting Command+Shift+G and entering “~/Music/iTunes/iTunes Media/Tones/” as the path</li><li><strong>iTunes:</strong> go to the Tones folder, and right-click on any ringtone choosing “Show in Finder”</li></ul><p>The iTunes approach may be better for many users because it doesn’t involve the file system as much.</p><p><img src=\"http://cdn.osxdaily.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/show-ringtone-location-itunes.jpg\" alt=\"Show the ringtone location quickly with iTunes\" title=\"show-ringtone-location-itunes\" width=\"620\" height=\"226\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-35052\" /></p><p>Once you’re in that directory, the m4r files can be copied, backed up, edited, shared with friends, or whatever else. From OS X 10.8 onward, you can right-click on any of the m4r files within that directory and use AirDrop or iMessage to immediately send it to someone else, though they will need to download and sync the ringtone manually because sending the file directly to an iPhone doesn’t allow it to be imported.</p><p>Keep in mind that ringtones you purchased from iTunes are going to have a different licensing schemes associated with them than ringtones you made yourself out of sound effects and audio clips or dug them out of the <a href=\"http://osxdaily.com/2011/04/15/900-secret-iphone-ringtones/\">gigantic secret collection from GarageBand</a>, it’s your responsibility to know what you can and can’t do with those files, but it’s a safe bet that if you paid for them the licensing agreement is such that it prevents sharing.</p><p>Finally, if you don’t see a ringtone in that folder but one is definitely on your iPhone, you’ll need to sync the device with iTunes on that computer to copy it over.</p></div><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=ZzW8OY_4clY:GSzYXQIBgmI:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=ZzW8OY_4clY:GSzYXQIBgmI:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?i=ZzW8OY_4clY:GSzYXQIBgmI:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=ZzW8OY_4clY:GSzYXQIBgmI:D7DqB2pKExk\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?i=ZzW8OY_4clY:GSzYXQIBgmI:D7DqB2pKExk\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=ZzW8OY_4clY:GSzYXQIBgmI:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?a=ZzW8OY_4clY:GSzYXQIBgmI:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/osxdaily?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/osxdaily/~4/ZzW8OY_4clY\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/osxdaily/~3/ZzW8OY_4clY/" (20692 45305) new 3 nil nil ((title nil "Quickly Locate iPhone Ringtones & Text Tones Stored Locally") (link nil "http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/osxdaily/~3/ZzW8OY_4clY/") (comments nil "http://osxdaily.com/2012/12/21/iphone-ringtone-text-tone-location/#comments") (pubDate nil "Fri, 21 Dec 2012 18:56:57 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Paul Horowitz") (category nil "iPhone") (category nil "Tips & Tricks") (category nil "iphone ringtone") (category nil "ringtone") (category nil "text tone") (category nil "tips") (category nil "tricks") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://osxdaily.com/?p=35050") (description nil "iPhone ringtones and text tones &#8211; both of which are .m4r files &#8211; are stored in the same location in the file system, whether they were made with iTunes, bought from the iTunes Store, converted from another format with QuickTime, or whether you downloaded them from elsewhere. The ringtone storage folder in OS X is: [...]") (content:encoded nil "<div class=\"KonaBody\"><p><img src=\"http://cdn.osxdaily.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/iphone-ringtone-folder.jpg\" alt=\"iPhone ringtone folder\" title=\"iphone-ringtone-folder\" width=\"620\" height=\"246\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-35051\" /></p><p>iPhone ringtones and text tones &#8211; both of which are .m4r files &#8211; are stored in the same location in the file system, whether they were <a href=\"http://osxdaily.com/2010/09/04/make-free-iphone-ringtones-in-itunes-10/\">made with iTunes</a>, bought from the iTunes Store, <a href=\"http://osxdaily.com/2012/08/18/convert-any-audio-or-video-to-iphone-ringtone-easily/\">converted from another format</a> with QuickTime, or whether you downloaded them from elsewhere.</p><p>The ringtone storage folder in OS X is:</p><p><code>~/Music/iTunes/iTunes Media/Tones/</cod